This is the opening line of India's Digital Personal Data Protection Act (DPDP Act). In simple words, this law creates a balance between two things: first, keeping your personal data (like your name and phone number) safe so that no one misuses it and second, allowing companies or the government to use that data in a lawful manner when needed.
​For example: When you order food from a food delivery app, it is necessary for that app to have your home address so the delivery boy can reach your house. This is a correct and necessary use of data (lawful purpose). However, after the arrival of this law, that company cannot sell your address to another advertising company without your consent, because protecting your data is your right.
